Today is the third week of advent. Gaudete Sunday! Gaudete means to rejoice in anticipation of the Lord, so I pray we can all have a moment of a shift in perspective to see all there is to be grateful for in our lives, because gratitude is the root of joy. And we have so much to be grateful for.
.
Today, while teaching catechesis of the Good Shepherd, and presenting on the visitation of Mary to Elizabeth, I asked the children, “why do you think the baby in Elizabeth’s womb leapt when he heard Mary’s voice?” One child answered “because she’s God’s mommy!” That totally struck me. It also showed me the simplest way to understand the Catholic appreciation of Mary. Rejoicing in Mary is rejoicing in Her Son because she is always leading us to Him. With the eyes of a child we can see Mary as a “mommy” and not just a “mother”.
.
She brings us joy on this Gaudete Sunday because she is the way by which He came to us. We can never go wrong following her way to lead us back to Him. She bore Him, the God-Man. What incredible joy.

Do you have a safe space you like to visit when things are particularly stressful? It helps me to remember that while I may feel stretched and weighed down by a lot at the moment, I have so much to be grateful for. I’m so glad those things can coexist. You do not have to choose. You can be grateful and also mourning the loss of something or someone, overflowing with joy and also panged with sadness.
.
It’s okay to remind our bodies in the times where distress or discomfort are engaged due to some kind of trigger that we are in fact safe and richly blessed even when we may not feel it in the moment.

It just means all that hard work preparing and waiting for him has also prepared us for this moment. God is good, all the time.

Jesus was born amidst turmoil. And Joseph, Mary, the shepherds, the wise men all rejoiced in His birth. This is my reflection and really all I have the energy these days to meditate on: “The people who walked in darkness have seen a Great Light.”
.
We all have darkness in our lives; there is so much turmoil in our world. And this is exactly what our Savior chooses to enter into as the most vulnerable creature that exists, a newborn baby. A poor refugee baby at that.
.
Make no mistake, God is with you no matter where you are and what the circumstances of your life are right now. And though there is much to grieve, there is so much more to rejoice in because the Great Light enters into our darkness and shows us the Way. ⭐️

“The world promises you comfort, but you were not made for comfort. You were made for greatness.” Rest in Peace Pope Benedict XVI.

Wow. This year was a lesson in an even deeper layer of the coexistence of joy and grief. We have been overwhelmed with joy in bringing Raffi into the world, into our family. It feels like he has always been here. And it broke our hearts to have to put our tiny pup down after only one year with her due to a fatal condition.
.
This has been a year in learning to let go, mourn, and be grateful all at once. Raffi’s birth was traumatic, from the time the doctor called an OB stat to when Raffi was out it was about 10 minutes. I was given general anesthesia whilst in transition and so I was not conscious for his birth. Thanks be to God we were/are both healthy. Thank God for good doctors and nurses and midwives! Boy did I feel cheated out of an experience I longed to have after losing two babies back to back.
.
Breastfeeding has been a doozy this time around. I officially stopped nursing a couple weeks ago and now I only pump but Raffi receives most of his nutrition from formula. It proved to be nearly impossible due to a sub mucous cleft palate, silent reflux, failure to thrive and low supply and thrush in myself. Thank God for formula and that Raffi is now above his growth curve and at the same time I am truly mourning the loss of nursing him.
.
We finally got an autism diagnosis for Henry and an ADHD diagnoses for him and Fulton and that has opened up new perspectives and lots of learning about the incredible way they experience the world. My kids continue to teach me so much everyday.
.
There has been a lot of loss this year but I have also never been so overwhelmed with joy and so much to be grateful for. I mean truly deeply grateful.
.
I am excited for what 2023 will bring. Hopefully as we get more in the swing of having 5 kids I will get to create new art and maybe new products and projects!
.
I’m pumped for the new year. How are you feeling about it?!

I think the beauty of parenthood is actually the reality that there are no expert parents. Why is that? Each human being is entirely unique and unrepeatable. There is no one size fits all parenting method/tool/trick/hack, there is no rule/playbook. There’s some great science, history, psychology, and wisdom to help inform us but ultimately it is a matter of faith, surrender, and being on a journey.
.
I believe the Holy Spirit guides us on the journey but the journey is a long messy road of failing, learning, and growing and He walks with us through it all.
.
I’m just grateful and joyful to be on that journey, however confusing, difficult, and overwhelming it may become.
.
Who else was the perfect parent before they became a parent? 🙋🏻‍♀️

I have been overwhelmed with emotion watching and reading about what is happening in Turkey and Syria. I get that we can only take in so much information and so I try to take it in in bits. And that is what has hit me the most, my privilege to do so. I have thought lately about the tiniest difference of my baby being born here in the US (I know it’s far from perfect here) and my baby being born in Turkey or Syria which was already devastated by conflicts, bombings, and man made destruction.
.
I have had so many questions and laments for God watching a literal newborn baby being pulled from the rubble (ALIVE!) and so many more incredible but grief stricken moments as it’s all unfolding. I feel a connection to these people on the other side of the globe. My heart breaks for them. It has helped me to gain perspective of the privileges of my life. I do not want to squander them and I want to dig deeper to understand what my role is in fighting for all of us to have the same privileges, so that others do not have to live with the constant threat of war, poor infrastructures, and fear of death.
.
My suffering is real, I am not diminishing it. It can coexist while I also recognize how others do not have most of the privileges I have in this world. I do not want to squander it.
.
If you have any good resources or ways to help Turkey and Syria please let me know, I will share in my stories!

Not Fawnly related but this was a highlight of the year for me so far. Since the moment the announcement was made that a @supermariomovie would be made we have been excitedly anticipating it as a family! We watched every new trailer and teaser that was released as they released them, and geeked over all the fun features that came out like the Super Mario Bros. Plumbing interactive website!
.
There’s something deeper in it for me than just the nostalgia of my first video game I ever played coming to “life” on a big screen. Henry (the tall guy in the Mario hoodie) is autistic and his interests are very specific and there aren’t many but what he loves he pours his whole self into. Some people call it hyper focusing, some call it an expertise. Super Mario Bros. is one of them. He can name any Mario game, the characters in them, the theme music in it, the special features and items specific to that game.
.
So when we saw this movie yesterday, the very first showing available in opening day, I made sure to sit by him to get the inside scoop on where all the references were coming from in the movie, he knew so many!
.
Why is this so special to me? In my experience, the way to grow close to someone you love who’s autistic is to visit their world with them, and become interested in the things they’re interested in.
.
That’s not always easy when it’s something entirely foreign to you or that doesn’t interest you at all. But with Super Mario Bros. it has been easy. I have fond memories of bonding with siblings playing Super Mario World on Super Nintendo and Super Mario 64 on Nintendo 64.
.
Now I get to watch my own boys bonding with each other over a game about brothers who are incredibly close and always looking out for each other.
.
It’s kind of an indescribable feeling having this full circle moment and bonding with my boys, especially Henry, through a video game.
.
It’s Autism Awareness Month and I definitely want to help others grow in awareness but I also hope we can continue to grow in acceptance by entering into their world a bit and seeing and loving them as the awesome people they are.

There’s a few new releases coming soon that I’m very excited about but in the meantime, this Summer break so far has been filled with a lot of joy and memory making. I haven’t had much time to create new designs in this stage of life but I’m being present to where God has me. I know in time I’ll be back to creating but for now God is working very interiorly in me. I have a new Hashimotos diagnosis which explains a lot of random symptoms for years that I’ve had. First tattoo. Only those who have known me a long time know how wild it is that I bit the bullet and got a tattoo. When my boys asked me why I want a permanent drawing on my body I told them it was because I have them here physically with me but I don’t have their siblings here in that way, this was as close as I could come other than having their blood mixed in with mine. And I could not be more happy with it. @pearl_and_rose_tattoo did an incredible job of making this come to life. She specializes in fine line work, is so skilled, professional, accommodating and comforting. Her studio is clean, cute, and calming. Can’t say enough good things.
.
On my tattoo my mama wrote Helen’s name and my grandma wrote the second baby we lost, Julia. My other grandma is also named Julia and she left this world two years ago. My sister and Kami drew the tattoo and I wrote JMJ, for Jesus, Mary, and Joseph. Hydrangeas are significant for many reasons in my life, they symbolize my relationship with Cory, and they mean “vessel”. Peonies symbolize compassion. I am just so grateful to have such a beautiful piece of art that means so much to me on me forever.
.
I also highly recommend tattoo numbing cream, worked like a charm 👌🏼.
.
If you’re in the area or near Garrett, IN and looking for a tattoo artist, reach out to Kami @pearl_and_rose_tattoo !

I read a quote recently that said “the pause between the trigger and the response is where the healing happens.” That quote spoke right to me and it was exactly the reflection I needed in that moment. This journey of healing is never over but sometimes it feels like I have not come that far. However, when I look back on how far I’ve come I realize there are pauses now when I’m triggered and before I respond that never existed before. And that is worth not only noting but celebrating and praising God and my therapist for 😆🥳.
.
So if you haven’t been to therapy before let this be your sign to book the appointment because there isn’t a single soul who doesn’t need it, and if it’s possible for you to go and you feel you could use some help in your growth/healing process then go! It’s a process, it takes time, but I’m telling you, it is so so worth it, and everyone in your life will benefit from it more than anything else you could do for them.

This was a collaborative effort with my son Pio, age 7. We were thinking of what decor to make for his new room. He LOVES Toy Story, but most especially Forky. So I drew him a Forky with a rainbow splatter behind him. Then I asked him what he wanted me to write. He asked if he could write it himself. So I handed it over.
.
This is what he gave back to me. Such simple wisdom. If you’ve never seen Toy Story 4 (first of all, you need to) Forky is a spork that was made into a beloved toy to a little girl who was nervous on her first day of school. Woody helped Forky to realize he’s valuable and loved because the person who created him did so with purpose and love. It’s not a perfect analogy but I found it a profound lesson when we’re tempted to treat ourselves as though we are trash. We were created from nothing but Who created us and what He created us for is invaluable.
.
Hope you can find some joy and encouragement from Forky and Pio today 🚯🗑️❤️🥄

This is my daily prayer. I’ve been asking God to expand my capacity to know, acknowledge, and help however I can with what is happening in Gaza and Israel and all other Palestinian territory. It is easy to feel completely helpless. But I know the only way war and genocide can manifest is through dehumanization. And that is largely what has happened for centuries especially this region of the world. So the greatest and most powerful act of rebellion I can think of and feel a pull toward is humanization. I will not ignore these Palestinians, many of whom are Palestinian Americans that are trapped there right now, and I will never justify any violence inflicted on Israelis. I will emphasize their humanity.
.
One night at bedtime my then 8 year old said to me, “Mom, it really seems like our family is special. Like there is something different about us.” Knowing he was just innocently observing how well loved he feels I said to him, “I think that’s because we are. The truth is that everyone is as special as you feel and are, but some people have forgotten it or don’t know it at all. It’s our job to help them see how well loved and special they are. We don’t want everyone to be alike, we want everyone to know how unique and unrepeatable they are.” Sometimes we fall back on preconceived notions, stories (lies) we’ve been told about people since childhood, messaging and poor representation in media, and just flat out ignorance and we slowly dehumanize people in our minds. We “other” people. When I find this sickness in myself I start with acknowledging it and accepting that I have that bias and prejudice and then I work to untangle the lies and seek truth asking “God, who do you say that they are?”.
.
I’m rambling now. I just want to say I am heartbroken every time I read or see images of what is happening in Gaza right now and I hope we can all refuse to dehumanize and let it break our hearts so that we combat and uproot the seeds of war and hate. And please, please pray for all those who have been affected by the violence in the Middle East as well as the humanitarian crisis in Gaza. 🙏🏼

I grew up with this painting in my home and was always haunted by it, rarely willing to look at it for very long. But now after much suffering of my own and the current unspeakable humanitarian crisis unfolding in the Middle East I find Mary of the Dagger to be almost a comfort. She knows this gruesome violent horrific suffering and tragedy.
.
I am not sharing this to spark a debate and I refuse to argue one’s value over another.
.
The most vulnerable, women and children, are being sacrificed in this conflict and it is tragic and horrific. I want every Palestinian and Jew to know they are not forgotten and I desire for Palestinians to be free and not used as human shields or treated as though they are less than human. Lord, have mercy.
.
I have nothing profound to say, I just started painting as a way to work through suffering and I care greatly about justice and mercy so this is important to me and I sure hope it’s important to you too. I know it is easy to grow weary of the tragedies. It’s okay to take a break and care for yourself. And please, PLEASE do not stop praying for these people, they are begging for us to not forget them.

I haven’t made art in a long time. I’m certainly out of practice. But art has always been my prayer and I think it’s not only OKAY to make ugly art, it’s IMPORTANT. We imitate our Creator the most when we create whether it’s beautiful or not, He will guide us closer to Him as we imitate Him and create what weighs on us the most. So get ready for some ugly art in this feed and go make some right now if you are out of practice, jumbled up inside, or just don’t think you’re artistic at all. Get going, don’t worry about the end result, trust He is working in the process.

I never draw people. EVER. This is why 😆. But it’s important to take risks and make ugly art. It’s a part of the process. Don’t be afraid to mess up and not be perfect! We need to get away from the mentality that it is only worth posting or sharing with the world if it’s perfect. Go make something just okay or even ugly, it’s a part of the process!
I’m sorry if you were ever made to feel differently. ❤️
Come Holy Spirit, bring your peace.

He is amidst the rubble of our lives, literally and figuratively. He comes as innocence incarnate but not ignorance. He comes to show us the Way. We can not bomb our way to peace. His Way requires humility. It requires slowing down, unfurling our fists, kneeling at his lowly manger, and asking Him what He makes of all of the mess in our hearts, in our Church, in our world. And then we must follow where He asks us to go.
.
That is Hope. That is Peace. That is Joy. That is Love.
.
The fullness of God in our hearts is a bottomless well of love, hope, and joy, and the absence of Him is a bottomless well of hatred, vengeance, and war.
.
Weary hearts, we must draw from His well. We belong to each other because we are united in Him. I pray you find a way to care for another human today, in little or big ways, because they are all significant. Every time we care for another human being it is significant, it is like medicine for Christs wounded, battered and broken Body.
.
I care for you all and I’m praying for you today. ❤️

Today is the feast of Our Lady of Guadalupe. I am no expert on the Catholic teachers of Our Lady of Guadalupe or the documented historical context from when Mary appeared to Juan Diego. However, from the little I know (thanks to info @fabiolagarzacreates  shared with me) it seems Mary appeared to an indigenous peasant of the Nahua people with the features of a woman indigenous to the region. She came to tell him that She is a Mother to ALL people and that we are all in her fold and care.
.
What a profound message. No one is excluded from the love and care of the Mother of God.
.
On this day I ask that we pray for Our Lady of Guadalupe to bring her message of provision, care, love and peace to all of her children.
.
Our Lady of Guadalupe, pray for us.
